# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1933-world-series
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1933-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The **1883 major league baseball season** was contested from May 1 through September 30, 1883.
[src:1933-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] It was the second season for the American Association (AA) and eighth season for the National League (NL).
[src:1933-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Philadelphia Athletics won the AA pennant, while the Boston Beaneaters won the NL pennant.
[src:1933-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] There was no postseason, although there was a canceled exhibition series between the two pennant winners.
[src:1933-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Prior to the season, the Troy Trojans and Worcester Worcesters of the National League folded.
[src:1933-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] In its place, the league enfranchised two teams: the New York Gothams and Philadelphia Quakers (today's San Francisco Giants and Philadelphia Phillies).
[src:1933-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] It was decided that the six-team American Association would expand to eight teams and saw the minor league New York Metropolitans join and the enfranchisement of the Columbus Buckeyes.
[src:1933-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Prior to the season, the Boston Red Caps and St.
[src:1933-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Brown Stockings renamed as the Boston Beaneaters and St.
[src:1933-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The American Association and the National League, along with the Northwestern League, sign the Tripartite Agreement (also known as the National Agreement).
[src:1933-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] This agreement binds the leagues to respect each other's valid player contracts as well as increasing the size of the reserve list from 6 to 11 players.
[src:1933-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The 1883 schedule consisted of 98 games for all teams in the American Association and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:1933-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 14 games against the other seven teams of their respective league.
[src:1933-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] This format was unique to the 1883 season.
[src:1933-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Previously, the National League had played an 84-game schedule, with 12 games against each team being played, while a pre-expansion six-team American Association had played an 80-game schedule, with 16 games against each team being played.
[src:1933-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The following season would see the National League play a 112-game schedule (increase of 14 to 16 games each), while the American Association would expanded again, this time to twelve teams, for a 110-game schedule (of 10 games against each of the other eleven teams).
[src:1933-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on May 1 featuring all sixteen teams.
[src:1933-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] American Association would see its final day of the regular season on September 30 featuring four teams, while the National League would see its final day of the regular season on September 29, featuring all eight teams.
[src:1933-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] 6 tie games (1 in AA, 5 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again) occurred throughout the season.
[src:1933-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Louisville Eclipse and New York Metropolitans had one tie game each.
[src:1933-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Cleveland Blues and Detroit Wolverines had three tie games each.
[src:1933-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Buffalo Bisons and Philadelphia Quakers had one tie game each.
[src:1933-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Polo Grounds, home of the New York Metropolitans and Gothams, featured two baseball fields, at the southeast and southwest of the grounds.
[src:1933-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The Gothams played entirely at the southeast grounds, while the Metropolitans moved alternated.
[src:1933-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The played ten games at the southeast diamond to start the season, before moving to the southwest diamond on May 30.
[src:1933-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] The southwest diamond was of worse quality than the southeast diamond, so games at the southwest diamond did not last long.
[src:1933-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] They played only ten games (aside from a one-off at the southeast diamond on June 13) before returning to the southeast diamond in July.
[src:1933-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] They did play three more games at the southwest diamond on August 30, 31, and September 4 due to scheduling conflicts with the Gothams.
[src:1933-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] Following a fire and a flood of their home at Exposition Park, the Pittsburgh Alleghenys had to move into a newly built venue, a second iteration of Exposition Park, which was built immediately south.
[src:1933-world-series/1883-major-league-baseball-season] However, after only 17 games, they played their last game there on June 9 and returned to the first Exposition Park on June 12.
[src:1933-world-series/1883-new-york-gothams-season] The **1883 New York Gothams season** was the first professional baseball season played by the team now known as the **San Francisco Giants**.
[src:1933-world-series/1883-new-york-gothams-season] The team replaced the Troy Trojans when the National League awarded its franchise rights to John B.
[src:1933-world-series/1883-new-york-gothams-season] The team went 46–50, finishing in sixth place.
[src:1933-world-series/1884-new-york-gothams-season] The **1884 New York Gothams season** was the second season of that baseball franchise, eventually known as the San Francisco Giants.
[src:1933-world-series/1884-new-york-gothams-season] The team finished in fourth place, 22 games behind the pennant-winning Providence Grays.
[src:1933-world-series/1886-new-york-giants-season] The **1886 New York Giants season** was the franchise's fourth season.
[src:1933-world-series/1886-new-york-giants-season] The team had a record of 75–44, finishing third in the National League, 12.5 games behind the Chicago White Stockings.
[src:1933-world-series/1887-new-york-giants-season] The **1887 New York Giants season** was the franchise's fifth season.
[src:1933-world-series/1887-new-york-giants-season] The team finished in fourth place in the National League with a record of 68–55, 10+1⁄2 games behind the Detroit Wolverines.
[src:1933-world-series/1887-new-york-giants-season] The team amassed 415 stolen bases, the most for any team in the history of the National League.
[src:1933-world-series/1888-new-york-giants-season] The **1888 New York Giants season** was the franchise's sixth season.
[src:1933-world-series/1888-new-york-giants-season] Claiming six future Hall of Famers (Roger Connor, Mickey Welch, Buck Ewing, Tim Keefe, Jim O'Rourke, and John Montgomery Ward), the team won the National League pennant by nine games and defeated the St.
[src:1933-world-series/1888-new-york-giants-season] Keefe led the league in several major statistical categories, including wins, winning percentage, strikeouts, and earned run average.
[src:1933-world-series/1888-new-york-giants-season] The Giants beat the American Association champion St.
[src:1933-world-series/1888-new-york-giants-season] Louis Browns in the World Series, six games to four.
[src:1933-world-series/1933-world-series] The **1933 World Series** was the championship series of the 1933 Major League Baseball season.
[src:1933-world-series/1933-world-series] The 30th edition of the World Series, it matched the National League (NL) pennant winner New York Giants and the American League (AL) pennant winner Washington Senators.
[src:1933-world-series/1933-world-series] The Giants defeated the Senators in five games for their first championship since 1922 and their fourth overall.
[src:1933-world-series/1933-world-series] Key to the Giants' World Series triumph was the pitching of aces "King" Carl Hubbell and "Prince" Hal Schumacher.
[src:1933-world-series/1933-world-series] This would be the last World Series played in Washington, D.C., until 2019.
[src:1933-world-series/1933-world-series] The Giants next won the World Series in 1954, their final title in New York City as the franchise moved to San Francisco after the 1957 season.
[src:1933-world-series/1933-world-series] New York Giants majority owner John McGraw retired as manager in 1932 after 30 years at the helm, naming his protégé, young star first baseman Bill Terry, recently the last .400 hitter in the National League, as his player-manager successor.
[src:1933-world-series/1933-world-series] Somewhat similarly, former superstar hurler Walter Johnson also retired in 1932 as Washington Senators manager in favor of young star shortstop Joe Cronin as their new player-manager.
[src:1933-world-series/1933-world-series] The Senators were the surprise team of 1933, breaking a seven-year monopoly on the AL title jointly held by the New York Yankees and Philadelphia Athletics from 1926 to 1932.
[src:1933-world-series/1933-world-series] But this could also be called a joint 13-year monopoly by all three, since the Senators had also won in 1924 and 1925 and the Yankees won from 1921 to 1923.
[src:1933-world-series/1933-world-series] 43-year-old future Hall of Famer Sam Rice, in his last year with the Senators, had only one at bat during the series, picking up a pinch hit single in the second game.
[src:1933-world-series/1933-world-series] Mel Ott had four hits and three RBI in Game 1, hitting a two-run home run in the first and RBI single in the third with two on, all off Lefty Stewart.
[src:1933-world-series/1933-world-series] Travis Jackson scored the Giants' last run on a groundout off Jack Russell.
[src:1933-world-series/1933-world-series] Carl Hubbell struck out ten, allowed two unearned runs (on groundouts by Joe Cronin in the fourth with two on and Joe Kuhel with the bases loaded in the ninth) and pitched a five-hitter.
[src:1933-world-series/1933-world-series] The Giants overcame a 1–0 deficit (as a result of Goose Goslin's third inning home run) with a six-run sixth inning.
[src:1933-world-series/1933-world-series] They loaded the bases with no outs on a single, double and intentional walk off General Crowder before Lefty O'Doul hit a pinch-hit single that scored two runs.
[src:1933-world-series/1933-world-series] RBI singles by Travis Jackson, Gus Mancuso, Hal Schumacher and Jo-Jo Moore each scored a run.
[src:1933-world-series/1933-world-series] Hal Schumacher pitched a five-hitter for a 6–1 victory, giving New York a 2–0 lead.
[src:1933-world-series/1933-world-series] The Senators scored two runs in the first inning on Joe Cronin's RBI groundout with runners on second and third followed by Fred Schulte's RBI double.
[src:1933-world-series/1933-world-series] Next inning, Ossie Bluege hit a leadoff double and scored on Buddy Myer's double.
[src:1933-world-series/1933-world-series] They got one more run in the seventh when Luke Sewell singled, stole second, moved to third on a groundout and scored on Myer's double.
[src:1933-world-series/1933-world-series] Earl Whitehill held New York to five hits in the shutout.
[src:1933-world-series/1933-world-series] To date, this is the last World Series game in which a Washington team won at home.
[src:1933-world-series/1933-world-series] Carl Hubbell went all eleven innings in the 2–1 win.
[src:1933-world-series/1933-world-series] He induced Cliff Bolton to ground out into a bases-loaded, game ending double play.
[src:1933-world-series/1933-world-series] Bill Terry's home run off Monte Weaver put the Giants up 1–0 in the fourth, but the Senators tied the score in the seventh when Joe Kuhel reached on an error, moved to second on a sacrifice bunt and scored on Luke Sewell's single.
[src:1933-world-series/1933-world-series] Travis Jackson singled to lead off the 11th, moved to second on a sacrifice bunt, and scored the game winning run on Blondy Ryan's single.
[src:1933-world-series/1933-world-series] In the second, Hal Schumacher's two-run single with runners on second and third put the Giants up 2–0 off General Crowder.
[src:1933-world-series/1933-world-series] Kiddo Davis hit a leadoff double in the sixth and scored on Gus Mancuso's double to extend the lead to 3–0.
[src:1933-world-series/1933-world-series] Fred Schulte hit a game-tying three run homer in the sixth after two, two-out singles. for the Senators.
[src:1933-world-series/1933-world-series] Mel Ott's second home run of the series in the tenth off Jack Russell won the Series for New York.
[src:1933-world-series/1933-world-series] Dolf Luque earned the win with 41⁄3 shutout innings of relief for Schumacher.
[src:1933-world-series/1933-world-series] At the time, the winning margin of five runs was second-lowest for a five-game series (later equaled in 1942 and 1974); the 1915 margin was two runs, and three runs in 2000.
[src:1933-world-series/1933-world-series] This was the last time postseason baseball was played in the nation’s capital until 2012, when the Washington Nationals (formerly the Montreal Expos) captured the #1 seed in the National League but were upset in the NLDS after being one strike away from eliminating the St.
[src:1933-world-series/1933-world-series] Louis Cardinals after their early 6–0 lead had evaporated.
[src:1933-world-series/1933-world-series] The Nationals would eventually win the World Series in 2019 in a major upset over a 107-win Houston Astros team in seven games, which ended a 95-year championship drought for the nation’s capital, dating back to the Senators' only title in 1924.
[src:1933-world-series/1933-world-series] This first Washington Senators franchise became the Minnesota Twins during the 1960–61 offseason, and would not reach the World Series again until 1965, where they fell to the Los Angeles Dodgers in seven games.
[src:1933-world-series/1933-world-series] The Twins would eventually win the World Series again in 1987 over the St.
[src:1933-world-series/1933-world-series] Louis Cardinals in seven games after being five innings away from elimination in Game 7, ending a 63-year championship drought.
[src:1933-world-series/1933-world-series] The second Washington Senators, inaugurated in 1961 to replace the first edition on its way to Minnesota, became the Texas Rangers in 1972, who were also defeated four games to one in their first World Series ever by the now San Francisco Giants in 2010.
[src:1933-world-series/1933-world-series] The Rangers were then defeated again in 2011 by the St.
[src:1933-world-series/1933-world-series] Louis Cardinals in seven games after being a strike away from the championship twice in Game 6.
[src:1933-world-series/1933-world-series] On their third attempt in 2023, they defeated the Arizona Diamondbacks in five games.
[src:1933-world-series/giants-season] The **1885 New York Giants season** was the franchise's third season.
[src:1933-world-series/giants-season] The team finished in second place, 2 games behind the Chicago White Stockings.
